'''Kamonaraita Shrine''' (かもならいたじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|qid=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in {{ill|lt=Kanan, Osaka|Q2305508|qid=Q2305508|1=Kanan, Osaka}}, {{ill|lt=Minamikawachi District|Q1347323|qid=Q1347323|1=Minamikawachi District, Osaka}}, {{ill|lt=Osaka Prefecture|Q122723|qid=Q122723|1=Osaka Prefecture}}. It is a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|qid=Q134917286}}, and under the former {{ill|lt=shrine rank|Q10444029|qid=Q10444029|1=Shakaku}} system it was a {{ill|lt=Sonsha|Q134917284|qid=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}}.

=== Enshrined deities ===
The principal enshrined deities are Nigihayahi-no-Mikoto, Amasu Teru Chiteru Hikohomino-Mikoto, and Kushitama-no-Mikoto, but all are alternate names of {{ill|lt=Nigihayahi|Q10949054|qid=Q10949054|1=Nigihayahi}}. Because this area was within the sphere of the {{ill|lt=Mononobe clan|Q1755836|qid=Q1755836|1=Mononobe clan}}, this is considered a shrine that took the Mononobe ancestral deity Nigihayahi as its main deity. However, because the shrine name contains "Kamo," there is also a theory that the original deity was related to the {{ill|lt=Kamo clan|Q122979436|qid=Q122979436|1=Kamo clan}}.

In the auxiliary sanctuary, {{ill|qid=Q125400|lt=Takamimusubi|UNKNOWN|lt=Taka-mi-musubi no Mikoto|1=Takamimusubi}} is enshrined.

=== History ===
Its founding background is unknown, but it is thought to date from before Engi 7. It is listed in the {{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|qid=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}} as "Kamonaraita Shrine, Ishikawa District, Kawachi Province" and classified as a minor shrine, but it later declined and its location became unknown.

The present Kamonaraita Shrine was a shrine that, until the Meiji period, was called "Tenmangū" and enshrined {{ill|lt=Sugawara no Michizane|Q382005|qid=Q382005|1=Sugawara no Michizane}}. In November {{ill|lt=1660|Q7001|qid=Q7001|1=1660}} (Manji 3), because the shrine building of nearby Tenjin Kamiyama Shrine, which enshrined Taka-mi-musubi no Mikoto, was destroyed by a storm, it was merged into this shrine. It was identified as the Shikinai Kamonaraita Shrine, renamed to its present shrine name, and the principal deity was changed to Nigihayahi-no-Mikoto. In Meiji 5, it was ranked as a village shrine.

